post_cb({"bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_27768899_27768972_1": {"length": 18, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 5381}, "so_27768899_27768899_0": {"length": 11, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 5430}}, "n3337": {"so_27768899_27768972_1": {"length": 18, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 5175}, "so_27768899_27768899_0": {"length": 11, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 5225}}, "n4659": {"so_27768899_27768972_1": {"length": 18, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 6805}, "so_27768899_27768899_0": {"length": 11, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 6858}}}, "27768899": {"ViewCount": "240", "Body": "<p>7.1.6.1/1 contains the following statement (emphasis mine):</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_27768899_27768899_0\">There are two <em>cv-qualifiers</em>, const and volatile. <strong>If a <em>cv-qualifier</em>\n  appears in a <em>decl-specifier-seq</em>, the <em>init-declarator-list</em> of the\n  declaration shall not be empty</strong>.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>What is the relevance of the statement in bold above? In other words, is it possible to produce an example of a <strong>cv-unqualified</strong>  type in a <em>decl-specifier-seq</em>, in which the <em>init-declarator-list</em> of the declaration is empty?</p>\n", "AcceptedAnswerId": "27768972", "Title": "What is the relevance of this statement in 7.1.6.1/1 in the C++ Standard?", "CreationDate": "2015-01-04T18:31:16.573", "Id": "27768899", "CommentCount": "0", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastActivityDate": "2015-01-04T18:57:35.390", "Score": "7", "OwnerUserId": "2548699", "Tags": "<c++><c++11><const><language-lawyer><volatile>", "AnswerCount": "1"}, "27768972": {"Id": "27768972", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>Sure, most class and enum definitions make use of it:</p>\n<pre><code>struct A { }; // valid\nconst struct B { }; // invalid, const would have no meaning\nconst struct C { } c { }; // valid\n</code></pre>\n<p>There is nothing else. An init-declarator-list is only used in a simple-declaration, and for that, the standard (C++11) states:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_27768899_27768972_0\"><strong>7 Declarations [dcl.dcl]</strong></p>\n<p id=\"so_27768899_27768972_1\">3 In a <em>simple-declaration</em>, the optional <em>init-declarator-list</em> can be omitted only when declaring a class (Clause 9) or enumeration (7.2), that is, when the <em>decl-specifier-seq</em> contains either a <em>class-specifier</em>, an <em>elaborated-type-specifier</em> with a <em>class-key</em> (9.1), or an <em>enum-specifier</em>.</p>\n</blockquote>\n", "LastEditorUserId": "743382", "LastActivityDate": "2015-01-04T18:57:35.390", "Score": "11", "CreationDate": "2015-01-04T18:39:07.133", "ParentId": "27768899", "CommentCount": "16", "OwnerUserId": "743382", "LastEditDate": "2015-01-04T18:57:35.390"}});